[1] Canada: duration in hospital
Date: Wed 2 Dec 2009
Surce: Digital Journal [edited]
<http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/283054>


Some Ontario swine flu victims kept in hospital for 3 months
------------------------------------------------------------
Some of the 1541 seriously ill patients have spent more than 3 months
in hospitals, the [Canadian] Ministry of Health reported in a weekly
bulletin. Ontario also says the case volume for swine flu [pandemic
(H1N1) 2009 virus infection} in the 2nd wave was up to 6 times higher
than the case load reached in the worst of the past 5 influenza
seasons going back all the way to 2004. The highest confirmed cases of
influenza in the past 5 flu seasons peaked at 500 cases in
mid-February of 2005 for the 2004-2005 seasonal flu outbreak. The peak
of the 2nd wave of swine flu reached some 2150 confirmed cases during
week 43.

Of the 1158 admitted to hospital between 1 Sep and 25 Nov 2009 -- the
2nd wave -- 222 remained hospitalized when the report was compiled;
and patients had a mean stay of 4 days but the range was between 0 to
94 days in hospital. 70 people died during the 2nd wave which is not
over yet and 25 died during the 1st wave which started in April
[2009], the report said.

A total of 8 of those hospitalized in the 1st wave remain in hospital.
"Admission to ICU [intensive care unit] and/or use of a ventilator was
reported for 21 percent (80) of wave one cases and 16 percent (186) of
wave 2 cases. Overall, 17 percent (266) of hospitalizations have been
admitted to ICU and/or placed on a ventilator. Fever, cough, shortness
of breath, vomiting, malaise, myalgia and sore throat/difficulty
swallowing have been the most commonly reported symptoms among
hospitalized cases," said the government report for the period ending
21 Nov 2009, but updated to 25 Nov 2009.

"16 new deaths were reported from 18 Nov 2009 to 25 Nov 2009 compared
to 18 new deaths reported from 12 Nov 2009 to 18 Nov 2009," said the
report.

- 101 of those hospitalized in Ontario were babies under one year old.
One infant died.

- 217 of those who were hospitalized were children aged 1 to 4 years.
There were no deaths in this group.

- 302 children between the ages of 5 to 14 were hospitalized. 5 died.

- 168 children and youths aged 15 to 24 were hospitalized. 7 died.

- 269 adults ranging in age from 25 to 44 were hospitalized with 16
deaths in this group.

- 343 people aged 45 to 64 were hospitalized, with 41 deaths in the age group.

- 141 people aged over 65 were hospitalized and they suffered the
highest death rate with 25 dead.

The figures suggest a higher hospitalization rate for younger children
but a higher fatality rate for older people.

--
