[2] China: blood donation
Date: Thu 3 Dec 2009
Source: The Shanghai Daily [edited]
<http://www.shanghaidaily.com/article/?id=421501&type=Metro>


City calls for blood in swine-flu war
-------------------------------------
Shanghai health authorities yesterday launched their latest drive in
the fight against swine flu [influenza pandemic (H1N1) 2009 virus
infection], calling on people who have been vaccinated against the
virus to donate blood for emergency-treatment storage. First in the
queue will be 34 inoculated medical staff at the Shanghai Public
Health Clinical Center, who are expected to donate blood today.

According to experts, a person starts to produce antibodies 3 weeks
after catching swine flu [influenza] or 2 weeks after vaccination.
Blood from these people can then be used to treat patients seriously
affected by the pandemic (H1N1) virus. "Using serum from vaccinated
staff to treat serious cases is mentioned in a treatment guide issued
by the Ministry of Health," said Dr Lu Hongzhou, a member of city's
expert panel on swine-flu treatment -- and one of the 34 expected
donors.

"The technology is safe and we have used it on our patients with good
results," Lu said. Since carrying out vaccinations on the most at-risk
groups of the population, such as medical staff, public servants and
students and teachers at primary and middle schools, Shanghai has
inoculated more than 800 000 people. A total of 2.1 million people
will be included in the vaccination plan, which has been expanded to
[include] university students and people aged 60 and over with local
residency.

By Monday, Shanghai had reported 2074 incidents of swine flu,
including 26 serious cases, since the 1st one was detected in May
[2009]. 2 young girls were still in critical condition in the city
yesterday with swine flu, while a Shanghai boy, aged 6, was off the
critical list and on the mend, officials from the Children's Hospital
of Fudan University said. A migrant girl, aged 3, from eastern China's
Anhui Province and a Shanghai girl, aged 6, were still on respirators,
the hospital said. The Anhui girl was showing stronger recovery signs,
said Wang Yi, the hospital's vice president. Since receiving the 1st
child seriously sickened by swine flu on 19 Nov 2009, the hospital has
treated 9 patients and 3 of them have recovered.

"We haven't used vaccinated people's serum in treating our child
patients as yet," Wang said.

[Byline: Cai Wenjun]

[Use of donated blood from vaccinated individuals for treatment of
pandemic influenza patients could be a hazardous procedure requiring
rigorous monitoring to prevent the transmission of blood-borne
infections. This form of treatment does not seem to have been used
extensively so far to establish its potential efficacy and safety.
Further information on the application of this drastic approach would
be welcomed. - Mod.CP]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshll

